@flexiarg ukrns/computation-as-exploration
@title Computational Modelling as Tension Exploration (Meta-Pattern)
@keywords meta-pattern, computational-modelling, inspectability, prior-not-posterior, exploration, exploration-vs-prediction, conditional-dependencies, live-table, declarative-assumptions, population-model
@audience UKRN-S design, working-paper authors, evaluators, futon developers, readers of the WP
@tone analytic-foundational
@style meta-pattern
@references [ukrns/ARGUMENT ukrns/diagnose-before-prescribing ukrns/measure-where-least-sure ukrns/design-as-function-of-evidence ukrns/self-application]

! conclusion: The working paper's population model and its figures, tables, and counterfactuals are not ends in themselves.  They are a device for making conditional dependencies between programme design, institutional context, and implementation outcome inspectable — so that the tensions in the five design patterns become visible, not hidden behind prose or folded into a single recommendation.  The service states which composition it is running on the axis between computation-as-exploration and computation-as-prediction, and for what reasons.
  + context: This is a meta-pattern: it describes how the working paper is constructed and why, and it also projects down into the service-design patterns because UKRN-S, like the paper, can use computation as an exploration device rather than a prediction engine.  In the paper, the population model is explicitly "a prior, not a posterior"; it does not predict what will happen but makes the conditional dependencies inspectable.  At the service scale, the same model re-runs operationally as new observations arrive (linked: ukrns/design-as-function-of-evidence).  The meta-pattern answers a common misreading: that the paper's computational apparatus is the paper's claim, when in fact it is the paper's method.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: computation-as-exploration (model used to make dependencies inspectable) ↔ computation-as-prediction (model used to produce forecasts on which policy rests).
    Real: a model used purely for exploration gives up the aggregated authority of predictive claims; a model used for prediction gives up the transparency that lets a reader see why the axes matter.  Both uses are legitimate in different contexts.  Both cost something real.
    Irreducible: the same model cannot simultaneously be maximally inspectable (showing every conditional dependency as adjustable) and maximally predictive (closed-form enough to fund a decision on).  Inspectability requires the dependencies to be open for revision; prediction requires them to be closed.
    Active: early in a programme's evidence cycle, exploration is the epistemically honest use because the prior is thin and posteriors are wide; as the evidence base thickens and posteriors tighten, predictive claims become defensible.  The right position on the axis shifts as the programme matures.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Explore-only: computation used exclusively to make tensions inspectable; no predictive claims offered; all figures serve the argument.  This is the paper's current position.  Gives up the aggregated authority of forecast-style claims.
    (2) Explore-now-predict-later: exploration in the current cycle, with predictive claims deferred to later cycles once the posterior has tightened sufficiently.  Gives up early predictive commitments that might have supported the funding case.
    (3) Parallel lines: an exploratory model for internal design deliberation and a separate predictive reporting line for funder and public communication.  Gives up the unity of the argument; carries the risk that the two lines drift apart.
    These compositions are not ranked; the paper is deliberately at Composition (1) and says so.  The choice recurs each time a new cycle of evidence is summarised.
  + BECAUSE:
    Prior-not-posterior as method: The model is explicitly declared a prior throughout the paper.  This is not a hedge; it is a method.  The claim 'this is what the landscape looks like at Stage 1 given Cycle-0 coding' is a claim about conditional dependencies, not about aggregate outcomes.  The value of information targeting (ukrns/measure-where-least-sure) depends on this stance: if the model were posterior, VoI targeting would already be exhausted.

    Declarative assumptions: The population model is specified in assumptions-v2.edn, a declarative data file.  Readers can change its values and rerun; they can audit its inputs separately from the computation that consumes them.  The separation of data from computation makes exploration a first-class operation.  (Contrast: a model whose assumptions are embedded in code — the same model in spirit, but no longer exploratory in this sense.)

    Sensitivity as humility: The sensitivity table (variant gate aggregation; variant support headroom) shows which claims are robust to modelling choices (direction: stages advance viability) and which are not (precise point estimates).  This is the exploratory stance made visible: the paper reports what the exploration recovers and what it does not.

    Reimplementable engine: Annex B specifies the pattern-strength equations, mode probabilities, lever definitions, and uncertainty model in enough detail that a reader could reimplement the model in any language.  This reimplementability is the exploration stance's strongest evidence: the computational claim is that the conditional dependencies matter, not that any particular implementation does.

    Multi-dimensional trade-off display (exemplar: vsat.wiki/analysis-demo): A strong instance of the exploration stance is the vsat business-models demo, which displays three named scenarios (services-first, hybrid, software-first) scored on multiple dimensions (financial surplus, local capability formation, network growth, public spillover) without ranking them.  Software-first wins on surplus (GBP 87k) but loses on local capability (9 stewards) and network growth (1 link); services-first loses on surplus (GBP 16k) but wins on local capability (24 stewards) and network growth (4 links); hybrid sits between.  No single scalar collapses the dimensions.  A reader picks the dimension that matters to them and sees which scenario does best on it.  The design principle this pattern inherits: any computational result that functions as a recommendation has collapsed too much of the trade-off surface.  The working paper's intervention-variance figure (three bundles × ten profiles), capability trade-off table (§3), openness/governance Pareto table (§4), and update-policy table (§5) are in this spirit.  The D × A mode probabilities deserve care — P(multiplied) as a single number risks becoming an implicit target if presented without its multi-dimensional context; the paired worked contrast (ukrns/worked-contrast) is one way the WP keeps that context visible.

    Projection into main patterns: if UKRN-S is a learning system that updates design as a function of evidence (ukrns/design-as-function-of-evidence), computation is one way — arguably the most inspectable way — to do that.  The service can use the same model operationally: as diagnoses update, as measurement waves complete, as update policies fire, the model recomputes and re-emits its argument.  The meta-pattern projects into the main patterns: the design patterns are service-design decisions; this meta-pattern is a description of one medium through which those decisions can be made inspectable.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: every computational artefact in the paper (figure, table, counterfactual) is traced to the axis or tension it is making visible; no figure exists as decoration; the model's inputs are inspectable and re-runnable; predictive claims, if made at all, are explicitly labelled as such.
    Failing when: the model's outputs are cited as if they were observations; figures exist for aesthetic or evidentiary weight rather than to make a tension visible; assumptions are embedded in code rather than declared; predictive claims are made without acknowledging the shift from prior to posterior.
  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - For each figure/table/counterfactual in the working paper, state which axis or tension it is making visible; excise any that cannot be so traced
    - Maintain assumptions-v2.edn as a declarative artefact readers can inspect and rerun
    - Maintain the reimplementation pointer (Annex B equations) so the computational claim is not locked to any one implementation
    - For operational use at UKRN-S: rerun the model after each measurement wave (ukrns/measure-where-least-sure) and publish what changed in the inspectable view
    - Report sensitivity variants whenever a claim depends on a specific modelling choice; distinguish robust direction from non-robust point estimates
    - Label any predictive claims explicitly and state the posterior evidence they rest on
  + INVARIANT-STATEMENT:
    Every computational artefact in the working paper (and in the UKRN-S operational model, if operationalised) has a stated role in making a tension inspectable.  Assumptions are declarative and separable from computation.  Sensitivity to modelling choices is reported.  Predictive claims, if made, are explicitly distinguished from exploratory claims.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Computation-as-authority: figures cited as if observations; the model treated as oracle rather than device
    - Assumption opacity: inputs embedded in code; reader cannot separate data from computation
    - Sensitivity-blindness: claims reported without testing alternative modelling choices
    - Implicit prediction: claims slide from prior-framed to posterior-framed without the shift being marked
    - Aesthetic computation: figures exist for evidentiary weight rather than for making a specific tension visible
    - Reimplementation-blindness: model described only operationally, not in terms re-implementable from first principles
    - Exploration-frozen: the exploratory stance is adopted at paper time but never revisited; as the evidence base matures, predictive claims never become explicit even when they would be defensible
    - Single-scalar collapse: the trade-off surface is reduced to one number that functions as an implicit recommendation; reader loses the ability to see the dimensions the scalar averaged over.  'P(multiplied) = 0.61 for this profile' risks becoming 'a score to raise' rather than 'a position on a D × A surface whose dimensions are in tension'
    - Single-recommendation framing: a multi-dimensional result is narrated with a preferred direction, quietly foreclosing the reader's freedom to weight dimensions differently
  + ANCESTORS:
    - UKRN WP draft-16-april (whole): the paper is the instance of this meta-pattern
    - UKRN WP §3 Limitations of the model ('the model is a prior, not a posterior')
    - UKRN WP Annex B (pattern strength, mode probabilities, levers, uncertainty model — reimplementable from first principles)
    - assumptions-v2.edn (declarative-assumptions artefact)
    - Sensitivity table (WP §3; gate aggregation variants, support headroom variants)
    - vsat.wiki/analysis-demo (business-models demo; three named scenarios × multiple dimensions; no ranking; an external exemplar of computation-as-exploration in practice — 'less dependent on a single abstract score', 'inspectable and open to revision in a way that a hidden scalar is not')
    - equity/ARGUMENT (the theoretical framing; computation is one medium through which that theory becomes inspectable at service scale)
    - ukrns/design-as-function-of-evidence (the operational projection of this meta-pattern)
    - ukrns/measure-where-least-sure (VoI targeting requires the prior stance)
  + DERIVATION:
    Derived from the working paper's consistent epistemic stance: the model is a prior used to make conditional dependencies inspectable, not a posterior used to forecast.
    Meta-pattern character: describes how the working paper is constructed and why, and also projects into the service-design patterns as an implementation hint.
    Projection into main patterns: ukrns/design-as-function-of-evidence specifies that the service updates on evidence; this meta-pattern names one medium (computational modelling) for doing so inspectably.  ukrns/measure-where-least-sure depends on the prior-stance; ukrns/diagnose-before-prescribing uses the computed D × A factorisation as its diagnostic engine.
    Axis framing follows the same Tension / Composition / Check structure as the main patterns.  Real / irreducible / active defence of the axis is load-bearing.
    Coordination requirement: Low at paper time (single author team can adopt the stance); Medium to High at service time (network-scale operationalisation requires shared access to the model and its assumptions).
